    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3254850889" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3254850889" />
    <a title="Mark Porton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18643650-mark-porton"><img alt="Mark Porton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591876752p2/18643650.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3254850889?book_show_action=true">Apr 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Porton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Porton" href="/user/show/18643650-mark-porton">Mark Porton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6336901-plainsong">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark-porton?shelf=5-stars">5-stars</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3254850889" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2226959527440036464"><b>Plainsong by Kent Haruf</b><br/><br/>Trying to think of one word to describe this book – I would say “Brooding”. <br/><br/>After about twenty pages I decided this was a book I needed to read slowly and deliberately. It was a slow burning, moody piece of work which made me feel. For what this book lacks in dialogue, it makes up for in atmosphere, space and anticipation.<br/><br/>There’s only a handful of characters, each wonderfully portrayed by the author. My favourites were poor little Victoria Roubideaux and the McPherons.<br/><br/>How </span>
  <span id="freeText2226959527440036464" style="display:none"><b>Plainsong by Kent Haruf</b><br /><br />Trying to think of one word to describe this book – I would say “Brooding”. <br /><br />After about twenty pages I decided this was a book I needed to read slowly and deliberately. It was a slow burning, moody piece of work which made me feel. For what this book lacks in dialogue, it makes up for in atmosphere, space and anticipation.<br /><br />There’s only a handful of characters, each wonderfully portrayed by the author. My favourites were poor little Victoria Roubideaux and the McPherons.<br /><br />How could anyone one not feel for this young girl? The cards she had been dealt, the choices she made and the fascinating journey she takes us on in this book – her journey. There were parts of her story that made me feel sorry for her and some that just made me feel helpless as her tale of woe unfolded. <br /><br />Whereas the McPheron brothers, these odd isolated old men were surprisingly central to this story. Some of their conversations with each other were hilarious such as when Harold was comparing Victoria to a two-year-old calf-carrying heifer with regards to sleeping patterns. Raymond was dumbfounded. <br /><br />I’ve read many terrific books over the years but this one is right up there. It engendered similar feelings to those I felt when I read The Grapes of Wrath, which is perhaps my all-time favourite.<br /><br /><b>5 Stars</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="2226959527440036464" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


